# {{ .prefix }}-reviewing-adr

<!-- awf:section when-fires -->
## When this skill fires

Terminal step of `{{ .prefix }}-proposing-adr`. Invoked once the ADR file is written and committed (status `Proposed`). The `adr-reviewer` subagent owns the review discipline: it reads the ADR, runs its internal lenses, classifies each finding as mechanical / reasoned / user-decision, applies fixes with a 3-round soft cap, and returns a digest. This skill dispatches that agent, surfaces the digest, gates on user-decision findings, and chains to the next node.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Procedure

<!-- awf:section procedure -->
1. **Identify the ADR path.** If the user named it explicitly, use that path. Otherwise, use the most recently-modified file under `{{ .layout.adrDir }}/` matching the `NNNN-*.md` pattern.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section artifact-path-detection -->
1. **Path detection detail.** When no explicit path is given: list `{{ .layout.adrDir }}/NNNN-*.md` sorted by modification time (newest last). Take the last entry. If no files match, stop and ask the user for the path.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section dispatch-subagent -->
1. **Dispatch the `adr-reviewer` subagent.** Invoke the agent tool with subagent type `adr-reviewer` and a brief that includes:
   - The absolute ADR path.
   - The instruction to return findings as `[{focus, severity, location, issue, suggested_fix, classification}]`.
   - The commit convention: apply fixes as new commits (never `--amend`) using the `{{ .vars.commitScope }}` scope.

   The agent handles lens application, finding classification, fix application, and the re-review loop internally. Do not re-describe those steps here.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section classify-route-findings -->
1. **Surface the digest, then route the findings.** Display the digest the `adr-reviewer` agent returns to the user. Then route the classified findings by classification kind, not severity:
   - **mechanical** — agent applies directly.
   - **reasoned** — agent applies with one-line rationale.
   - **user-decision** — present to the user and wait.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section apply-fixes-commit -->
1. **Commit applied fixes.** Fixes are committed as new commits (never `--amend`) using `{{ .vars.commitScope }}` scope. The agent handles the Edit calls; this skill ensures the commit convention is followed.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section re-review-loop -->
1. **Re-review loop.** The `adr-reviewer` agent manages the re-review loop (3-round soft cap) and escalates residual structural findings as `user-decision` items. Do not issue further dispatch without explicit user direction.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section status-flip -->
1. **Flip ADR status when finalised.** After the review settles (no structural findings, or user decisions resolved), flip the ADR `status:` frontmatter from `Proposed` to `Accepted`. Flip to `Implemented` instead if this ADR ships its own code in the same commit series. Commit the flip.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section hand-off-to-resync -->
1. **Hand off to plan resync.** After the ADR review converges and the status is flipped, check whether a plan exists (a `{{ .layout.plansDir }}/YYYY-MM-DD-*.md` file named or implied by the ADR). If a plan exists, invoke `{{ .prefix }}-reviewing-plan-resync` against that plan. If no plan exists, the chain proceeds directly to implementation.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Notes

<!-- awf:section notes -->
- If the user asks to skip review, comply but warn that a chain step is being skipped.
- See `{{ .layout.workflowRef }}` for full ADR lifecycle rules and the canonical workflow chain.
- The `adr-reviewer` is one lens-diverse subagent; this skill does not fan out per-lens subagents or specify per-lens model routing.
<!-- awf:end -->
